**PLEASE NOTE**

As of September 1, 2020 student meals (breakfast and lunch) will be FREE for ALL students. This is currently scheduled to last until December 31, 2020 or until there are no longer federal funds available.

Any meals charged to your account for the month of September will be credited back. Students will continue to pay for a la carte items and any seconds they wish to have. This is available for students learning from home as well. Please let the office know by 9 am if your child would like a grab-n-go lunch that will be picked up at 10:30 am. If you have any questions, please contact the school office at 402-698-2377.

post_text:
Good Afternoon Parents, Family, and Friends

Attached is the latest revision of the Return to School Plan.
The latest revision reflects input from the community, staff, and board; and ongoing conversations and guidance from health care professionals.

Particularly, I direct your attention to page 2 – the two essential objectives and the three fundamentals, as it pertains to successfully returning to school.

Please email or call Mr. Lembke or me with questions, thoughts, and concerns. We welcome face-to-face conversations.

Also, Sunday, August 16 and Monday, August 17, virtual meetings will be held. The purpose will be to share the plan, take questions, and listen to input. More details will be shared later this week through email, the website, and the district Facebook page.

Gregg Cruickshank
Superintendent/Elementary Principal
Homer Community School
greggcruickshank@homerknights.org
402-404-9869

You can also view the Return to School Plan on our Website with the following link:

https://www.homerknights.org/vnews/display.v/ART/5f330162debb8

**Important Sports Physical Information**
Incoming 7th and 9th graders need physicals, but incoming 8th, 10th - 12th graders for whom we have a physical on file do not need new physicals. PLEASE NOTE ALL 7TH GRADE STUDENTS WILL NEED A PHYSICAL, EVEN IF THEY AREN'T PARTICIPATING IN SPORTS.
Everyone participating in a sport needs the other 3 components to the paperwork (NSAA, Ambulance, Concussion).
All forms can be found on the school website under Athletics, General Information or you can pick one up at the school office.

post_text:
Homer Community School would like to welcome our new 5th Grade Teacher, Nicholle Olson!

Hello Homer Community! My name is Nicholle Olson. I recently got married to my high school sweetheart, Tanner, who is also a Homer alumni! I graduated from Wayne State College with a degree in Elementary Education this past May. For the past few years, I have worked for Homer as a substitute teacher. I am so excited to be back at Homer teaching 5th grade! I can’t wait to begin teaching alongside an amazing group of staff and teachers.

Welcome, Nicholle! We are so glad you are here!

We wish you the very best, Rylee!

post_text:
Updated information regarding participation physicals for the 20-21 school year.

Students entering the 7th grade WILL still need to have a physical exam. However, the physicals that the current 7th graders have for the 2019-2020 school year CAN be used for NSAA purposes for the 2020-2021 school year.

All current 8th grade students that are going to enter the 9th grade in 2020, will STILL be required to get an athletic physical for the 2020-2021 school year. All other high school students entering grades 10, 11 & 12 grades that have a the athletic participation paperwork for 2019-2020 school year, can use that physical for the 2020-2021 school year.

Thanks,

Mr. Lembke

Update on all NSAA Activities:

All NSAA activity practices and competitions are suspended through May 1st. These suspensions may be extended should the conditions warrant.

Member schools and student-participants are expected to adhere to the NSAA Constitution & Bylaws and activity manuals during this time.

The NSAA encourages all member schools to follow CDC, local, state and federal health department recommendations.

As more information becomes available, official updates will be posted on the NSAA website and the NSAA social media platforms.

Dear Students, Staff, Parents, and Patrons:

The closing of normal school operations has been extended through Monday, April 13. This means the earliest possible date normal operations will resume is Tuesday, April 14. Staff will be meeting Tuesday, March 24 to continue working on the remote learning plan that was started on March 17. Details will be shared with the public on the district website, the district Facebook page, and School Messenger.

Gregg Cruickshank, Superintendent

post_text:
While Homer Community School hopes to have the capacity and approval to provide breakfast and lunch to students starting Monday, March 23, another "in the meantime" community resource has been made available to students in need of a meal:

Starting immediately, a Homer student will be able to receive an entree (chicken strips, personal pan pizza, sandwich, etc.) at Pronto when they identify themselves as a Homer Knight. No need to disclose or prove a need, but we ask that this is limited to once daily since the tab is being paid by a private donor (also, this does not include drinks or candy).

The only request made by the anonymous provider is to pay it forward: do what you can, when you can, to whom you can.

As soon as the school is given the green light to provide meals, applicable information will be shared with you. In the meantime, we do the next right thing.

post_text:
Dear Parents and Students,
During the closure, the administration is working with our food service provider, and the department of education nutrition services, to provide breakfast and lunch for our students. The desired option is to provide free lunch and breakfast. That option is more complicated for district’s with a free and reduced percentage less than 50. Homer’s is 47. More guidance is coming from nutrition services today. A program will be offered starting Monday, and details will be shared with the public through School Messenger by phone call and text message, Facebook, and the website. The School Messenger email function is not working.

Gregg Cruickshank, Superintendent
